---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro'
---

<ProjectLayout
  badge="Data Science & Machine Learning"
  title="Comparative Evaluation of Lightweight Supervised Machine Learning Techniques for Industrial Rotating Machinery."
  description="99.85% accuracy, zero false positives, 98.4% less energy than the cloud — predictive maintenance light enough to run on a $5 microcontroller."
  coverImage="/portfolio/images/cover_bdai.webp"
  coverAlt="IEEE BDAI 2026 — Industrial Fault Detection via Machine Learning paper cover"
  ogImage="https://alesso-24.github.io/portfolio/images/cover_bdai.webp"
  meta={[
    { label: 'Conference', value: 'IEEE 9th International Conference on Big Data and Artificial Intelligence (BDAI 2026)' },
    { label: 'Presentation', value: 'July 3–5, 2026 · Chongqing, China (remote)' },
    { label: 'Status', value: 'Accepted — Presenting Remotely' },
    { label: 'Index Terms', value: 'Predictive Maintenance, NASA IMS Dataset, Machine Learning, Random Forest, Logistic Regression, FDR' },
  ]}
>

  <!-- Abstract -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Abstract.</h2>
  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    This study evaluates the performance of three supervised machine learning algorithms —
    Random Forest (RF), Logistic Regression (LR), and Support Vector Machine (SVM) — in
    detecting bearing faults at different degradation stages using the NASA IMS dataset. The
    methodology involves computing statistical features (RMS, Peak, Crest Factor, Kurtosis)
    from vibration signals and employing the Fisher Discriminant Ratio (FDR) to separate the
    data into Incipient and Advanced fault stages.
  </p>

  <!-- Key stats -->
  <div data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120" style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit, minmax(180px,1fr)); gap:clamp(16px,2vw,24px); margin: clamp(32px,5vh,48px) 0;">
    {[
      { value: '99.85%', label: 'Accuracy' },
      { value: '0', label: 'False Positives' },
      { value: '98.4%', label: 'Less energy than cloud' },
    ].map(({ value, label }) => (
      <div style="background:#efe7d8; border-radius:12px; padding:clamp(20px,2.5vw,28px);">
        <div class="stat-highlight">{value}</div>
        <p style="margin:8px 0 0; font-size:13px; color:#6f6a5f; line-height:1.5;">{label}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Context & Introduction -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>I. Context & Introduction.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    The project follows a rigorous data science pipeline focusing on extracting time-domain
    statistical features from raw vibration data (984 files from NASA IMS Bearing 1).
  </p>
  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    Using the Fisher Discriminant Ratio to mathematically define when a bearing transitions
    from 'Healthy' to 'Incipient Fault', and finally to 'Advanced Fault'.
  </p>

  <!-- Fig paper1 -->
  <div data-reveal style="border-radius:18px; overflow:hidden; margin: clamp(24px,4vh,40px) 0; box-shadow: 0 24px 60px -30px rgba(37,64,192,0.3);">
    <img
      src="/portfolio/images/paper1.webp"
      alt="Algorithm Comparison — Performance vs Latency trade-off visualization"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      style="width:100%; height:auto; display:block;"
    />
    <div style="padding:16px 20px; background:#efe7d8; font:400 13px 'Hanken Grotesk',system-ui,sans-serif; color:#6f6a5f;">
      <strong style="color:#211f1a;">Algorithm Comparison.</strong> Performance vs Latency trade-off visualization.
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Feature Engineering -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>II. Feature Engineering.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    To ensure the model was lightweight enough for a microcontroller, the Fast Fourier Transform
    (FFT) was deliberately omitted — it requires
    <code class="inline-code">O(N log N)</code> complexity. Instead, the system evaluates
    the one-dimensional statistical temporal evolution of vibrations at
    <code class="inline-code">O(N)</code> complexity.
  </p>
  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    Candidate metrics (Shape Factor, Crest Factor, Skewness, Kurtosis) were computed. After
    Variable Importance analysis (Gini impurity), Root Mean Square (RMS) and peak amplitude
    dominated — ideal features due to their monotonic trend directly correlated to progressive
    physical wear.
  </p>

  <!-- Fig paper3 -->
  <div data-reveal style="border-radius:18px; overflow:hidden; margin: clamp(24px,4vh,40px) 0; box-shadow: 0 22px 50px -30px rgba(234,106,46,0.3);">
    <img
      src="/portfolio/images/paper3.webp"
      alt="Fig 2. Time-domain vibration analysis: healthy vs fault state"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      style="width:100%; height:auto; display:block;"
    />
    <div style="padding:16px 20px; background:#efe7d8; font:400 13px 'Hanken Grotesk',system-ui,sans-serif; color:#6f6a5f;">
      <strong style="color:#211f1a;">Fig 2.</strong> Time-domain vibration analysis: contrast between healthy operational state and critical fault.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Fig paper5 -->
  <div data-reveal style="border-radius:18px; overflow:hidden; margin: clamp(24px,4vh,40px) 0; box-shadow: 0 24px 60px -30px rgba(37,64,192,0.3);">
    <img
      src="/portfolio/images/paper5.webp"
      alt="Fig 3. Importance analysis: RMS value dominates as the most discriminative metric"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      style="width:100%; height:auto; display:block;"
    />
    <div style="padding:16px 20px; background:#efe7d8; font:400 13px 'Hanken Grotesk',system-ui,sans-serif; color:#6f6a5f;">
      <strong style="color:#211f1a;">Fig 3.</strong> Importance analysis: RMS value dominates as the most discriminative metric.
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Results & Edge -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>III. Results & Edge Computing.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    To prevent overfitting, hyperparameters were tuned via structured cross-validation over
    temporal cycles to isolate data leakage. The SVM and k-NN models proved competitive, but
    <strong style="color:#211f1a;">Random Forest (100 estimators) dominated with over 99% effectiveness.</strong>
    Reporting 0 false positives was the fundamental milestone for validating it as a safe
    emergency halt protocol without arbitrarily stopping the plant.
  </p>

  <!-- Edge Computing callout -->
  <div class="callout" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    <p style="font:600 12px 'Hanken Grotesk',system-ui,sans-serif; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#6f6a5f; margin:0 0 12px;">
      Edge Energy Relevance (ESP32)
    </p>
    <p style="margin:0; font-size:clamp(14px,1.2vw,16px); line-height:1.65; color:#534f46;">
      This approach was mathematically extrapolated to an IoT-connected architecture (ESP32-S3
      with an RTOS). By inferring the tree branches locally on hardware and using MQTT to
      transmit <em>exclusively</em> an alarm payload, the device consumes an estimated
      <strong style="color:#2540c0;">0.99 mJ per execution</strong> — a
      <strong style="color:#2540c0;">98% energy saving</strong> compared to streaming all raw
      data over Wi-Fi to the Cloud.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Confusion matrix -->
  <div data-reveal style="border-radius:18px; overflow:hidden; margin: clamp(24px,4vh,40px) 0; box-shadow: 0 22px 50px -30px rgba(234,106,46,0.3);">
    <img
      src="/portfolio/images/paper6.webp"
      alt="Fig 4. Optimized model confusion matrix — zero false positives or false negatives"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
      style="width:100%; height:auto; display:block;"
    />
    <div style="padding:16px 20px; background:#efe7d8; font:400 13px 'Hanken Grotesk',system-ui,sans-serif; color:#6f6a5f;">
      <strong style="color:#211f1a;">Fig 4.</strong> Optimized model confusion matrix — complete reliability with zero false positives (FAR = 0%).
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- CTA -->
  <div data-reveal style="text-align:center; padding: clamp(24px,4vh,40px) 0;">
    <p style="font:600 12px 'Hanken Grotesk',system-ui,sans-serif; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#6f6a5f; margin:0 0 16px;">
      Document Availability
    </p>
    <p class="prose" style="text-align:center; max-width:52ch; margin: 0 auto 24px;">
      Accepted to IEEE BDAI 2026; camera-ready manuscript submitted and registration fees paid.
      Proceedings will be published via IEEE Xplore and indexed in Ei Compendex and Scopus
      following the conference.
    </p>
